1048 Aere interp. cet.: Lucr. is here completely mistaken from too hasty an induction: neither the attractive nor the repulsive power of a magnet is sensibly affected by the interposition of any body which is not sensibly magnetical, be it metal glass wood paper or whatever else: nay the magnet works equally in a vacuum, the absence or presence of air making no difference: this by the way overthrows the poet’s argu- ment 1022-1041, where he brings in his favourite air to assist in ex- plaining the attraction between the loadstone and iron.
